Thx, for your bugreport. This is by design. Webshims trys to polyfill and normalize features through the jQuery API. While this isn't 100% native, it is a better solution, then most other scriptable shims provide, because we do not implement a new abstraction API, but use an already existing abstraction layer (jQuery). This is explained in the [docs](http://afarkas.github.com/webshim/demos/index.html#polyfill-abstractions).

This means everything should work as expected, if you are using $.attr/$.prop or $.val.

```
//set empty string (shows placeholder)
$('input').prop('value', '');

//set value (hides plyaceholder)
$('input').prop('value', 'some value');

//get value (does not return placeholder text)
$('input').prop('value');
```

Sorry, that this answer might not satisfy you.

For posterity, here's something that makes accessing 'value' directly work - note that this was only tested in IE9, as that was the only browser I wanted to patch. Might work in some others as well.

Essentially what this does is make sure that all access to 'value' is routed via jQuery's methods, and as such, the polyfill will work its magic.

Note: It's probably kind of hacky... ;)

```
(function() {
    var originalProp = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(HTMLInputElement.prototype, 'value');
    var settingProp = false;
    var gettingProp = false;
    Object.defineProperty(HTMLInputElement.prototype, 'value', {
        set: function(val) {
            if(settingProp) {
                originalProp.set.call(this, val);
                return;
            }

            settingProp = true;
            $(this).prop('value', val);


            settingProp = false;
        },

        get: function() {
            if(gettingProp) {
                return originalProp.get.call(this);
            }

            gettingProp = true;
            var val = $(this).prop('value');
            gettingProp = false;

            return val;
        }
    });

})();
```

Yeah, this is exactly the way,I would use, if I would not support IE6, 7 and 8. (IE8 has partial support for this, but can crash if used in combination with htc behaviors).

Webshims uses a very similiar API to extend jQuery properties. A pure idl attribute accessor implementation looks like this:

```
$.webshims.defineNodeNamesProperty('audio, video', 'currentTime', { 
    prop: { 
        get: function(){ 
            //your getter implementation ("this" refers to the element) 
        }, 
        set: function(value){
             //your setter implementation ("this" refers to the element) 
        } 
    } 
});
```

A content attribute implementation, which is reflected by an idl attribute:

```
$.webshims.defineNodeNamesProperty('input, textarea', 'placeholder', { 
    attr: { 
        get: function(){ 
            //your getter implementation ("this" refers to the element) 
        }, 
        set: function(value){
             //your setter implementation ("this" refers to the element) 
        } 
    },
    reflect: true, //true = default but there are different type for number, references to other elements, urls etc.
    initAttr: true // should the setter be invoked initially, if attribute is available
});
```

This is a known issue and has to do with the odd way of changing the errormessages in HTML5 in conjunction with a non-standard FF extension. (see: https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=655677)

The best way to workaround this:

```
/* remove error box-shadow in FF */
input, textarea, select { box-shadow: none; }

/* re-add error-box-shadow */
.form-ui-invalid { box-shadow: 0 0 1.5px 1px red }
```

